{"has_more_entries": true, "subscriptions": "", "error": "", "posts": [{"is_locked": false, "tweet_id": "", "sticky_comment": 0, "is_video_mp4": false, "type": "link", "uuid": "1ASsdr8ELt", "is_twitter": false, "is_admin": false, "score": 62, "suggested_sort": 0, "post_flair_class": "", "id": 8644895, "raw_content": "", "author": "TateDemarcus", "created": 1779982147030, "profile_picture": "", "community": "TheDonald", "ad_tier": 2, "last_comment_author": "booblitchutz", "is_video": false, "video_link": "", "is_new_user": false, "domain": "cdn.5mind.com", "is_crosspost": false, "preview": "https://media.scored.co/preview/1ASsdr8ELt.png", "removal_source": "", "link": "https://cdn.5mind.com/uploads/production/DrWrtAazt-_Hd1yNUhBYu/image/AjNzQaDXVgfcArm7VevFu.jpeg", "author_flair_class": "", "is_removed": false, "media": {"resized_resolutions": [{"reference": "/scale/9skItY3rXKVPOYPg.jpeg", "width": 624, "content-type": "jpeg", "height": 768}], "blurhash": "UGFO[nb[-7%L4mx[-:xu~B-oNIt866xaM{of", "full_resolution": [1329, 1079]}, "title": "Good Question!", "last_comment_created": 1779990656697, "content": "", "score_down": 0, "author_flair_text": "", "pro_tier": 0, "is_stickied": false, "is_nsfw": false, "is_deleted": false, "is_image": true, "comments": 5, "score_up": 62, "is_edited": false, "is_moderator": false, "awards": 0, "vote_state": 2, "link_metadata": {"status": 200}, "post_flair_text": "", "archive_id": ""}, {"is_locked": false, "tweet_id": "", "sticky_comment": 0, "is_video_mp4": false, "type": "text", "uuid": "1ASsdsEyVp", "is_twitter": false, "is_admin": false, "score": 36, "suggested_sort": 0, "post_flair_class": "", "id": 8645285, "raw_content": "The Senate Majority Leader position is a party leadership role, not a constitutional office. John Thune (R-SD) was elected by the Senate Republican Conference in November 2024 to serve as Senate Republican Leader (and thus Majority Leader) for the 119th Congress.    \n    \nHow Removal Works: Only Senate Republicans can remove him from this role. The position is chosen and can be changed by vote of the Republican Conference (the caucus of all GOP senators). It is not subject to a full Senate vote or action by Democrats.    \n    \nProcess: A group of Republican senators can request a Conference meeting. According to Republican Conference rules (similar to those used in prior Congresses), the Conference Chair must convene a meeting if requested by at least 5 senators. A new leadership vote can then be held, typically by secret ballot if contested.     \n    \nTiming: This can happen at any time during the Congress (not just at the start), though it is rare and politically disruptive. Leadership terms are generally for up to two years (until the end of a Congress), but the Conference can act earlier.     \n     \nThreshold: A simple majority of voting Republican senators would be needed to elect a replacement.    \n    \nThis has never happened to a sitting Senate Majority Leader in modern history (replacements have occurred due to death, retirement, or party control shifts), but the mechanism exists.     \n    \nAlternative: Wait until the next Congress (2027) for a routine leadership election, though momentum could force an earlier challenge.", "author": "rdvs34283", "created": 1779992559345, "profile_picture": "p9HQtdiLq2uP", "community": "TheDonald", "ad_tier": 2, "last_comment_author": "I_Love_45-70_Gov", "is_video": false, "video_link": "", "is_new_user": false, "domain": "", "is_crosspost": false, "preview": "", "removal_source": "", "link": "", "author_flair_class": "", "is_removed": false, "media": {"resized_resolutions": [], "blurhash": "", "full_resolution": []}, "title": "I asked Grok how to remove John Thune as senate majority leader.", "last_comment_created": 1779998142870, "content": "<p>The Senate Majority Leader position is a party leadership role, not a constitutional office. John Thune (R-SD) was elected by the Senate Republican Conference in November 2024 to serve as Senate Republican Leader (and thus Majority Leader) for the 119th Congress.</p>\n<p>How Removal Works: Only Senate Republicans can remove him from this role. The position is chosen and can be changed by vote of the Republican Conference (the caucus of all GOP senators). It is not subject to a full Senate vote or action by Democrats.</p>\n<p>Process: A group of Republican senators can request a Conference meeting. According to Republican Conference rules (similar to those used in prior Congresses), the Conference Chair must convene a meeting if requested by at least 5 senators. A new leadership vote can then be held, typically by secret ballot if contested.</p>\n<p>Timing: This can happen at any time during the Congress (not just at the start), though it is rare and politically disruptive. Leadership terms are generally for up to two years (until the end of a Congress), but the Conference can act earlier.</p>\n<p>Threshold: A simple majority of voting Republican senators would be needed to elect a replacement.</p>\n<p>This has never happened to a sitting Senate Majority Leader in modern history (replacements have occurred due to death, retirement, or party control shifts), but the mechanism exists.</p>\n<p>Alternative: Wait until the next Congress (2027) for a routine leadership election, though momentum could force an earlier challenge.</p>\n", "score_down": 0, "author_flair_text": "", "pro_tier": 0, "is_stickied": false, "is_nsfw": false, "is_deleted": false, "is_image": false, "comments": 4, "score_up": 36, "is_edited": false, "is_moderator": false, "awards": 0, "vote_state": 2, "link_metadata": {"status": 200}, "post_flair_text": "", "archive_id": ""}, {"is_locked": false, "tweet_id": "", "sticky_comment": 0, "is_video_mp4": false, "type": "link", "uuid": "1ASsdr785g", "is_twitter": false, "is_admin": false, "score": 118, "suggested_sort": 0, "post_flair_class": "", "id": 8644488, "raw_content": "", "author": "NewBurner04", "created": 1779969193726,